Possible questions

  • how is one variable (price) distributed?
    • histogram
    • density chart
  • how is diamond price related to size? clarity? color? (relationship b/w two variables)
    • scatterplot
    • boxplot
  • how two variables are related conditioned on other variables ("faceting")
    • scatter plot by group
  • are some diamond colors more rare than others?
  • are the biggest diamonds usually high or low clarity?

With Dataset..

  • variables
  • types and ranges
    • categorical
    • ordinal
    • conti/discrete numerical
  • for a single varible:
    • how do values separate into groups(clusters)?
    • do the values have an asymmetric trailing off more in one direction than others?
    • undexpectedly popular or unpopular values?
    • centered? (mean vs. median)
    • how widely spread? (max-min or sd)

2. Distribution & key properties¶

  • median
  • mean
  • mode (most common value)
  • qurtiles : 25%, 50%, 75%
  • variance
  • extreme values (top 10%, bottom 90%, range)

Visualization with ggplot2¶

In [18]:
attach(diamonds)
qplot(log(carat), log(price), data= diamonds)
# results:
# positive linear relationship
# empty bars (missing values)
# outliers

    carat, clarity, color, cut, depth, price, table, x, y, z

Results:

  • interpreting a scatterplot
    • is there a global trend?
    • linear, curved, multi-part trend?

Aesthetic attributes of a plot

  • each aesthetic can be mapped to a variable
    • color, shape for categorical variable
    • size for conti. variable
  • each aesthetic attribute has a scale
    • scale maps data values to aesthetic values
    • ggplot will add a legend automatically if needed
In [20]:
qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, colour=color)
In [22]:
#qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, size=color)  # not good
In [24]:
#qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, colour=color, size=color)  # not good since it's too dense.

2. setting the alpha aesthetic (transparency)

In [26]:
qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, alpha=I(1/100))  
# I is a function/operator
In [27]:
qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, alpha=I(1/5))

3. Facets show the sample plot for different subsets of the data

  • can find outliers in the graph

qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, facets=~clarity)
In [31]:
qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, facets=.~clarity)
In [32]:
qplot(carat, price, data= diamonds, facets=clarity~color)

4. Geometric objects in ggplot : geom=".."

  • point
  • jitter
  • boxplot
In [38]:
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom="point")  # not so good
In [39]:
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom="jitter")
In [40]:
# layer different plots together
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom=c("jitter", "boxplot"))
In [41]:
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom="jitter", color=clarity)

5. Boxplot

  • help find outliers and summarize distributions
  • summrize 5 key values
    • median
    • low-hight extremem poitns
    • hinge : halfway from extreme to the median (Q1 & Q3)
In [42]:
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom="boxplot")
In [43]:
qplot(color, price/carat, data=diamonds, geom="boxplot", facets=~cut)  # .~cut can generate a different display
  • are some diamond color more rare than others?
In [47]:
qplot(color, data=diamonds, geom="histogram")

Data Manipulation¶

  • Subsets : to explore relationship b/w two varaibles
    • remove obviously 'bad' values
    • 'zoom in' on a region of interest
  • transforming : adding new columns of features
  • summarizing : statistics over groups in the data

group-wise transforms and summaries

  • like SQL GROUP BY statement
  • like map-reduce
  • example
    • rank of baby name within given year and sex

enter ddply

  • if we want to perform this same task for every sex in every year, split up the data, apply the transformation t...pieces
In [78]:
# input data, how to split input, function to apply to each piece, 2nd arg to transform
bnames <- ddply(bnames, c("sex", "year"), transform, rank = rank(~percent, ties.method = "first"))

regular expression

  • example : interesting whole-dataset transforms and summaries
In [85]:
vowels <- function(x){
    nchar(gsub("[^AEIOUaeiou]", "", x))
    # nsub : counts of # of each letter
    # gsub : global string replace using regular expression
}

In [89]:
letter <- function (x, n=1){
    if (n < 0){
        nc <- nchar(x)
        n <- nc + n + 1
        }
    tolower(substr(x, n,n))
}

Missing data

  • represented as NA
  • check : complete() function
  • if missing values are 999, then re-code 999 to NA
    • data <- ifelse(orig.data == 999, NA, orig.data)
  • delete any records that contain NA values
